Batch prompts on .txt file

You can create a batch of prompts, save it on a .txt file and use that file for automatic image generation.

The .txt file must be formatted as follow (as example with just 2 prompts):


positive: a girl is walking through street, raincoat, yellow umbrella

negative: (leave empty)

-------

positive:museum, people are looking paintings, abstract

negative: (leave empty)

-------


The file has to be saved in the following folder:

/custom_nodes/ComfyUI-Inspire-Pack/prompts/example/

full body, (woman 24-years-old :1.15), well-built, (green eyes:1.05), (almond eyes shape:1.05), serious, oval face-shape, (auburn hair color:1.05), (short hair length:1.05), natural skin, (detailed skin:1.4), (skin pores:1.2), (skin imperfections:1.02), (freckles:1.25), (eyes details:1.19), (iris details:1.19), (natural makeup:1.05), (ajusting hair pose:1.25), (sporty dress:1.25), sunrise warmth light, (professional photo, balanced photo, balanced exposure:1.2)

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
--LUT Module--

LUT are a kind of "filter" that allows you to modify your image colors, contrast saturation and tones, giving them an "analogic-film" look. You can find and download free LUT from many websites. I use mainly this one:

https://www.freepresets.com/product-category/free-luts-color-lookup-table/film-free-luts-color-lookup-table/

LUT files must be downloaded in the following folder: ../ComfyUI/custom_nodes/ComfyUI_essentials/luts/

Some of the most used analogic film were the following:
-Fuji Provia medium color-saturation and contrast. Wide range of applications, such as product, landscape, nature and fashion photography as well as portraiture.
-FUji Astia smooth and natural skin tone reproduction from the highlights to the shadows and exceptionally fine grain. Ideally suited for fashion photography and portraiture.
-Kodak Portra daylight-balanced professional color negative films originally introduced in 1998 made mainly for portrait and wedding applications.
-Fuji Velvia superb granularity, and world-class levels of image color-saturation and vibrancy. Vivid color reproduction and excellent image quality.
-Agfa Ultra 100
-Kodakcrome

widgets_values:
--Suggested Settings for portraits--

  1. Latent Upscale (rng 1.0 - 2.0): 1.20 - 1.50
    Best results around 1.25
  2. Flux guidance (rng 0.0 - 5.0): 3.00- 3.50
    Best results around original image Guidance
  3. Denoise (rng 0.45 - 0.90): 0.55 - 0.60
    High values may change the image
  4. Speed-Accuracy (rng 1.0 - 2.0): 0.50 - 0.75
    Latent injection steps: more = more details
  5. Noise Strength (rng 0.10 - 0.60): 0.30 - 0.40
    High noise strength will overcook images
  6. Rough-Smooth (rng 0.40 - 0.80): 0.60 - 0.70
    For portrait is better to stay above 0.60

nodes.title: Unnamed
widgets_values:
--Sharpen settings--

For portraits I suggest to use the following settings:

-Noise_radius: 7
-Preserve_edges: 0.60
-Sharpen: 3.0
-Ratio: 0.4

For other kind of image you could try with higher Sharpen values (6-7).

Image Comparer: Image A Latent Injection - Image B with Latent & ADetailer
Unnamed
widgets_values:
--Tenofas' FLUX - Modular Workflow v.4.1--

This workflow was created mainly for realitic portrait photos, but with all its modules it became extremely flexible and it allows you to use FLUX for any kind of image generation. This version can be used with the original FLUX Dev model or (new) the GGUF models for lower GPU/Vram (I suggest to try the Q4 GGUF model, gives great results and it is still very close to the original one). Just load your FLUX model, your LoRA's, write your prompt (or use one of the other prompt methods) switch on the modules you want to use for generating the image and press Queue. Sit back and relax, watching your image come to life.

Link to Workflow guide:

https://civitai.com/articles/6848/tenofas-flux-modular-workflow-user-guide


--The original FLUX model--

This workflow was designed for the original FLUX model released by the Black Forest Lab team. You will need the following files to use the workflow:

1) UNET - Dev or Schnell version (each one is around 24Gb, Dev gives better results, Schnell is the "turbo" version). Dev download Link: https://huggingface.co/black-forest-labs/FLUX.1-dev/resolve/main/flux1-dev.safetensors?download=true Schnell download LinK: https://huggingface.co/black-forest-labs/FLUX.1-schnell/resolve/main/flux1-schnell.safetensors?download=true

2) Clip - you need these clip files (use fp16 for better results, fp8 if you have low Vram/Ram).

t5xxl_fp16: https://huggingface.co/comfyanonymous/flux_text_encoders/resolve/main/t5xxl_fp16.safetensors?download=true

t5xxl_fp8: https://huggingface.co/comfyanonymous/flux_text_encoders/resolve/main/t5xxl_fp8_e4m3fn.safetensors?download=true

clip_l: https://huggingface.co/comfyanonymous/flux_text_encoders/resolve/main/clip_l.safetensors?download=true

3) VAE - last but not least the VAE file: https://huggingface.co/black-forest-labs/FLUX.1-dev/resolve/main/ae.safetensors?download=true

Warning: ADetailer needs a lot of Vram, so if you use the default Dev version with the fp16 t5 and have less than 24GB Vram you could have "out of memory" errors. In this case try the GGUF version, see below.


--The FLUX GGUF model--

This workflow can now run with the FLUX GGUF model that allows you to use FLUX even on computers with smaller GPU's and less VRAM.
GGFU versions of FLUX can be downloaded from here:
https://huggingface.co/city96/FLUX.1-dev-gguf/tree/main

I suggest you to use Q8 for best quality, but if you have Vram promblems (using ADetailer is very very Vram hungry) just try the Q4 Gguf version, I tested it with great results.


--ADetailer--

This detailer will enhance the face's skin and the eyes details using FLUX model and any LoRA you are using. These are the files you need for the mask detector:

1) samvitb_01ec64.pth (goes in folder /models/ultralytics/bbox/ )

https://huggingface.co/datasets/Gourieff/ReActor/blob/main/models/sams/sam_vit_b_01ec64.pth

2) faceyolov8nv2.pt (goes in folder /models/ultralytics/bbox/ )

https://huggingface.co/Bingsu/adetailer/blob/main/face_yolov8n_v2.pt

3) eyeful_v2-paired.pt (goes in folder /models/ultralytics/bbox/ )

https://civitai.com/models/178518/eyeful-or-robust-eye-detection-for-adetailer-comfyui

4) hand_yolov8s.pt (goes in folder /models/ultralytics/bbox/ )

https://huggingface.co/intellectusartificialis/adetailer/tree/main


--Latent Noise Injection--

The Latent Noise injection group is a sort of upscaler/detailer that works in the Latent space during the image generation. This module may modify the original image, so be very careful using its settings. It is also very easy to "overcook" the final image adding too much noise or setting too high noise strength. With the right settings it can highly improve your image, adding crisp details in every part of the picture. You can even change setting in the final Sharpen node, if you want do control details' "crispiness". Warning: handle with care!

---Img2img module---

For best results I suggest to use the Florence-2-large-PromptGen-v1.5 model, with fp32 precision.
Use the "img2img Denoise" selector (range 0.30 - 0.90) to choose the strength of the new image over the original input, higher values will modify more the final output making it closer to the prompt (above 0.85 the image may be completely different).  I suggest to stay between 0.4 and 0.6.
